articlebody:
Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau addresses Canadians on the COVID-19 pandemic from Rideau Cottage in Ottawa, Ontario, on Wednesday, April 1, 2020. (Sean Kilpatrick/The Canadian Press via AP) APAP
Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau warned the United States Friday that restricting medical supplies from being sent to Canada during the ongoing COVID-19 virus outbreak would be a "mistake." According to the Associated Press, Trudeau's comments came after U.S.-based manufacturing company 3M confirmed President Donald Trump's administration requested the company cease exporting respirators to Canada and Latin America.
3M responded by saying there would be "significant humanitarian implications" if the company stopped shipping supplies to those countries as 3M manufactures a critical amount of respirators for those nations. According to Politico, the company has also said it went "above and beyond" with its production in recent months having doubled production in January, ahead of the outbreak in the U.S.
As part of his warning, Trudeau said the U.S. is also receiving very important medical supplies from Canada that assist U.S. healthcare workers.
"These are things that Americans rely on and it would be a mistake to create blockages or reduce the amount of back-and-forth trade of essential goods and services, including medical goods, across our border," Trudeau said.
However, he did say he thought the message was getting through to the U.S. and expects there won't be any disruptions in the supply chain between the two countries. Last month, the countries agreed to allow for travel between the two nations for essential supplies which allows for various goods to be imported and exported while shutting down the rest of the border to non-essential travel.
